Title: Strategic Transparency and Informed Trading: Will Capital Market Integration Force Convergence of Corporate Governance?
Journal: Journal of Financial and Quantitative Analysis
Pages: 61-86
Issue: 01
Volume: 38
Year: 2003
Month: March    
Abstract: Dominant investors can influence the publicly available information about firms by affecting the cost of information collection. Under strategic competition, transparency results in higher variability of profits and output. Thus, lenders prefer less transparency, since this protects firms when in a weak competitive position, while equity holders prefer more. Market interaction creates strategic complementarity in gathering information on competing firms, thus entry by transparent competitors will improve price informativeness. Moreover, as the return to information gathering increases with liquidity, increasing global trading may undermine the ability of bank control to keep firms opaque.
